condition.narrative: Finance Agreement :4883 KZ | Description :- Establishment of the Health Policy Council | Due Date :01-Jul-2008
Finance Agreement :4883 KZ | Description :Maintain CCT and PIST with composition, resources, and TORs, satisfactory to the Bank. |Due Date :01-Dec-2008

Finance Agreement :4883 KZ | Description :The Borrower shall make the appropriate annual budget allocations to the MOH in line withthe agreed contributions to the project as agreed with the Bank at the beginning of each FY. | Frequency :Yearly

title.narrative: Improved financial risk protection as defined by reduced share of household health spending in total health expenditures
Master plans for capital investments, developed based on international best practice, used as a basis for capital investment allocations in at least 4 oblasts
Oblast-level health network master plans endorsed for at least 4 oblasts
At least two evidence-based disease management programs, which include incentives for health care providers and patients, developedand endorsed by the Ministry of Health
Increased capacity for health policy analysis (as measured by number of national analytical reports produced annually)
Increased funding for Primary Health Care
Health facilities constructed, renovated, and/or equipped (number)
Number of public health facilities accredited by national accreditation body in accordance with international standards
Decrease in absolute number of paid donations by 2015
Master plans for capital investments developed for 16 regions based on international best practice
Increase in share of voluntary blood donations by 2015
Drug price reference system for drugs included in the National Formulary Book developed and adopted by the Ministry of Health

target.value: Reference drug prices refined based on implementation experience

actual.value: Price-setting rules for drugs and medical supplies included in the State Guaranteed Free Health Care were approved through theMoHSD Order No.639 dated July 30, 2015.

title.narrative: Criteria, procedures and standards for accreditation of health facilities developed, adopted and implemented in line with international practice

target.value: Accreditation criteria, procedures and standards renewed

actual.value: National accreditation standards for inpatient care were certified by ISQua in 2012, and for outpatient care in 2013. Trainingprogram for surveyors was certified by ISQua in 2013. Accreditation standards for blood banks approved and for rehabilitation caredeveloped in 2015. Accreditation standards for inpatient, outpatient, and emergency care renewed in 2015 and shared with ISQua forendorsement.

title.narrative: IT-infrastructure for deployment of UHMIS in selected oblasts developed by the Ministry of Health

baseline.value: IT infrastructure developed in 140 health organizations

target.value: IT infrastructure developed in 2,000 health organizations

actual.value: Akmola: 140 health facilitiesKaraganda: 150Total: 290 health facilitiesIndicator was not achieved due to change in approach(e-Health instead of Unified Health Information System). IT equipment for all oblast-level health facilities shall be providedthrough respective local budgets (decision of the MoHSD Board taken in 2015).

title.narrative: New network planning tools and new facility standards formally adopted by the Ministry of Health

baseline.value: New hospital planning tools and standards developed

target.value: New tools and standards for planning hospitals, laboratory and PHC facilities formally adopted

actual.value: New tools and standards for planning hospitals, laboratory and PHC facilities were formally adopted through the new state standardof health facility network (GoK decree #114 dated Feb.19, 2014).

title.narrative: Evidence-based CPGs for selected disease management programs developed

baseline.value: No CPGs for disease management programs

target.value: CPGs for disease management programs implemented

actual.value: CPGs for three diseases (arterial hypertension, diabetes mellitus, and chronic heart failure) implemented in 7 pilot oblasts aspart of disease management programs.

title.narrative: Criteria, procedures and standards for accreditation of basic medical education programs developed, adopted and implemented in linewith international practice

target.value: Educational programs for “General Medicine” of two medical universities accredited

actual.value: National accreditation of educational programs was received by 5 medical universities (Astana Medical University, Karaganda StateMedical University, Semey State Medical University, South-Kazakhstan State Pharmaceutical Academy, and Kazakh National MedicalUniversity).

title.narrative: Evidence-based incentives for providers in disease management programs implemented

target.value: Optimized set of evidence-based incentives and pay-for-performance mechanisms for providers implemented

actual.value: Evidence-based incentives for providers have not been implemented. However, (i) process indicators have been included in theincentive-based component of the PHC capitation rate, and (ii) disease management program implementation has been included as oneof mandatory requirements for accreditation of health facilities providing outpatient care.

title.narrative: Functional ICT standards in line with major international functional standards developed by Health ICT Regulatory Body

actual.value: 5 functional standards developed and approved: electronic health record, electronic medical record, e-referral, electronic diseaseprevention, and e-prescription.

title.narrative: Incentives introduced, including revision of co-payments, for patients to comply with diseases management programs

target.value: Optimized set of incentives for patients implemented

actual.value: Incentives for patients have not been implemented in full. However, but non-financial incentives are being implemented in the pilotfacilities for DMP.

title.narrative: ICT standards, which conform with international standards and include interoperability standards, are endorsed by Health ICT Regulatory Body and published
Legal and regulatory documents related to post-processing food standards revised in accordance with international standards

baseline.value: Recommendations on revision of 26 food safety norms and rules, 25 technical regulations, and on amendments to the Law on FoodSafety developed

target.value: HACCP system implementation in food industry expanded

actual.value: Pilot implementation of HACCP system completed at 5 food industry enterprises in Karaganda oblast with project-supported technicalassistance. As of October 1, 2015, HACCP system implemented in 268 food industry enterprises in line with Technical RegulationNo.021/2011 of the Customs Union.

title.narrative: NHA reports produced annually, disaggregated by national and sub-national levels, and disseminated among key stakeholders
Project work plans, procurement plans, and budget produced and approved on an annual basis as described in the Project Operational Manual
